      • BamIndexFileWriterBuilder

        public BamIndexFileWriterBuilder(File inputBamFile)
                          throws IOException
        Create a new Builder instance with the given input BAM that will write a Bam index file to the same directory as the input bam and name it inputBamFile.getName() +".bai".
        API Note:
        this is the same as new BamIndexFileWriterBuilder(inputBamFile, new File(inputBamFile.getParentFile(), inputBamFile.getName() +".bai"))
        Parameters:
        inputBamFile - the input BAM file to parse and create an index from; can not be null, must exist and end with ".bam".
        Throws:
        IOException - if there are any problems creating any missing output files or if the input BAM file does not exist.
        NullPointerException - if inputBamFile is null.
        IllegalArgumentException - if the file extensions aren't correct.
        Since:
        5.0
        See Also:
        BamIndexFileWriterBuilder(File, File)

      • BamIndexFileWriterBuilder

        public BamIndexFileWriterBuilder(File inputBamFile,
                                 File outputBaiFile)
                          throws IOException
        Create a new Builder instance with the given input BAM and output index files.
        Parameters:
        inputBamFile - the input BAM file to parse and create an index from; can not be null, must exist and end with ".bam".
        outputBaiFile - the output BAM index file to write; can not be null and end with ".bai". If the output path does not exist, then the file and any non-existent parent directories will be created.
        Throws:
        IOException - if there are any problems creating any missing output files or directories or if the input BAM file does not exist.
        NullPointerException - if any parameter is null.
        IllegalArgumentException - if the file extensions aren't correct.

    • Method Detail

      • assumeSorted

        public BamIndexFileWriterBuilder assumeSorted(boolean assumeSorted)
        Assume that the given input BAM file contains SortOrder.COORDINATE sorted data even if the header says otherwise. If not called, by default, this value is set to false. If this value is set to false, then during the build(), the header of the input BAM is checked to make sure the sort order is set to SortOrder.COORDINATE and will throw an IllegalStateException if it's not.
        Parameters:
        assumeSorted - true if the header should not be checked and assumed to be SortOrder.COORDINATE; false if the header should be checked and fail if not (the default).
        Returns:
        this.

      • includeMetaData

        public BamIndexFileWriterBuilder includeMetaData(boolean includeMetaData)
        BAM Index files created by some other SAM libraries add additional metadata to the index such as the number of unaligned reads. This metadata is not specified in the BAM Index specification so some SAM parsers might not be able to correctly handle them. If this method is not called, then by default, the metadata is not included.
        Parameters:
        includeMetaData - true if metadata should be included; false otherwise (the default).
        Returns:
        this.

      • build

        public File build()
           throws IOException
        Actually parse the input BAM file and write out the corresponding BAM index file to the given output file.
        Returns:
        the output indexed File (this is the same file as was passed into the constructor)
        Throws:
        IOException - if there are any problems parsing the BAM file or writing out the index file.
        IllegalStateException - if the BAM file is not in SortOrder.COORDINATE order and assumeSorted(boolean) is set to false.
